comment:
Selfish People Canâ€™t Produce Unselfish Solutions

In Europe and elsewhere, governments are paying colossal sums to big corporations to help them avert bankruptcy. Whether they call it a â€œrescue packageâ€ or â€œquantitative easing,â€ in the end itâ€™s all the same: the government pays companies to stay operative.
I donâ€™t think it will work in the long run. It may keep companies afloat for another six months or a year, but as a rule, a government, any government, cannot sustain companies that cannot sustain themselves. In the end, the situation will blow up in a blast that will be worse than what it would have happened had the government let them fall naturally.
There is more to it than that. I donâ€™t believe that a government can do anything good for its people. Civil servants, ministers, and deputy ministers always pull their own way and have their own interests in mind. Since everyone is inherently selfish, everyone has an ulterior motive that is not for the benefit of the public.
We cannot expect selfish people to do unselfish acts; it is like asking a tiger to become vegetarian. If it goes against nature and it wonâ€™t work. Therefore, asking people whose only focus is their own career to focus on other peopleâ€™s well-being is unwise, unrealistic, and will invariably fail.
Socialists, capitalists, far right, or far left, they are all immersed in egoism. It is not their fault; it is human nature, and we should adjust our expectation from our leaders.
If we want a real and lasting positive change, we must transform human nature. Since our nature is selfish to the core, changing it is the only way out of the crises that the world is falling into nowadays. We will fall deeper and deeper until we realize that the problem is not the fuel we burn, the forests we cut, the water we pollute, or the people we kill. The problem is the cause of all those harms we are inflicting on nature and on each other: our inherent self-absorption. When we start working on changing ourselves rather than demanding everything and everyone else to change, we might be able to save ourselves before it is too late..

comment: I remember around 2002 on TV Berlin, they always played this music video in the afternoon. I came from grade school and would turn on the TV to dance to the music and really enjoyed it. One day I would go to my mother to show her the song I had found that I was always dancing to. She said "This is George Harrison." and I said "I really like the song he sings. I like him too because of it. He must be a great person." My mom then said "Honey, George Harrison doesn't live anymore." And for no other reason but it dawning on me that someone who's made me happy with his song for many weeks wasn't alive anymore , I burst into the biggest tears I'd never cried before. Will never forget that feeling of deep deep sadness. RIP George â¤ï¸

comment: "I had to practice the dance spot with Ringo in the hotel room before we filmed this video. The trouble was, they were filming a scene for Wallstreet down the hall, and Michael Douglas and his friends kept chasing us, I thought we were in A Hard Day's Night all over again. But once we signed some autographs, Ringo and I were back to practice and we nailed it. Ringo was great, very professional. comment: Whatâ€™s funny about this but at the same time sad? The fact of living in the mountains in a desolate area away from all family members and friends. The other idea of having to work for no paycheck around the clock seven months before seeing any kind of money whatsoever. My other thoughts were basically about the chair that he is sitting in. I used to sit in a very similar seat each morning before, during food and smoke breaks and after work to sit and watch television. I always sat in that same chair. The issue with this chair was not with me. It was with my TWO bosses. You see when I arrived at this cabin/farm property I had never received the history of the chair I loved so much. It wasnâ€™t until I moved out of the cabin to go to work independently that I found the information on the history of the chair. As for the history of â€œthe chairâ€ it was used only for the workers on the farm. Everyone else sat in other very nice seating. So with this being said..the men that used to farm here, cut down trees and work in the sewage tanks on the property and up in the mountains hunting or what have you Wood sweat all day and be filthy never take showers and sat in this chair every day. Video Director: "Right then George; pretend like you hate being here. Like its an absolute bother to your schedule to shoot this video."
 
George: "how so?"

George: "I dunno; I want a spunky video."

comment: This music video was filmed at GMT Studios in Culver City, CA. I know this because my dad was the general manager of the studios at the time. He casually came home one day and, over dinner, announced that George Harrison was filming a music video on one of their stages. My mom (an original Beatles fan) and I asked why he didn't get an autograph for us. My dad's reply was that he didn't want to bother him while he was working. There's still a grudge held in my family to this day. To this day...
